# Secure Development Principles

Source: cursor-security-rules. Apply to all development and AI-generated code.

## 1. No Raw User Input in Sensitive Operations
- Untrusted input must never be used directly in file access, command execution, database queries, or similar.

## 2. No Secrets in Public Code
- No API keys, credentials, private keys, or tokens in frontend code, public repos, or client-distributed files.

## 3. Secure Communication Only
- Use only HTTPS/TLS for external communications.

## 4. No Executing Dynamic Code
- Do not execute dynamically constructed code or expressions at runtime.

## 5. Validate All External Input
- Validate inputs from users, external APIs, or third-party systems before use.

## 6. No Sensitive Data in Logs
- Logs must not contain credentials, tokens, PII, or other sensitive data.

## 7. Do Not Disable Security Controls
- Do not bypass or suppress security checks without documented and reviewed justification.

## 8. Do Not Rely on Client-Side Only for Security
- Critical logic for permissions, authentication, or validation must not rely solely on client-side code.

## 9. No Hardcoded Credentials
- No credentials in source files, config, or scripts. Use env or a secure secrets store.
